Or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Holidays Are Coming
Subject: Critical Socio-Commercial Analysis / Festive Satire
Date: December 2025
Status: Seasonally Adjusted
Abstract
This paper presents a formal investigation into the most successful rebranding campaign in human history: the systematic transformation of Saint Nicholas from a green-robed bishop into a red-suited corporate mascot. We argue that the modern image of "Santa Claus" is not a natural evolution of folklore, but a calculated act of Chromatic Colonization designed to maximize fourth-quarter beverage sales.
Through rigorous analysis of historical iconography, we demonstrate that Santa's current appearance is a direct product of 1930s Coca-Cola advertising campaigns. The jolly red figure we know today is not authentic traditionâ€”it is Marketable Traditionâ„¢, a corporate fiction so successful it has retroactively edited our collective cultural memory.
However, in keeping with established methodology, we will conclude by systematically dismantling our own thesis and confessing that the "Holidays Are Coming" advert is, in fact, the pinnacle of human artistic achievement.
I. The Original Green: Historical Evidence of Pre-Commercial Saint Nicholas
1.1 The Bishop's Vestments
Historical records consistently depict Saint Nicholas of Myra (270-343 CE) in traditional bishop's robes, which in the Byzantine tradition were predominantly green and gold. The association with red vestments did not emerge until significantly later and had no connection to his charitable activities.
Key evidence:
Medieval manuscripts (12th-15th century) show variations including green, blue, and brown robes
Dutch Sinterklaas tradition maintained red bishop's robes, but with entirely different iconography (tall, thin, formal)
Victorian Christmas cards (pre-1930s) depict Father Christmas in green, white, or brown fur-trimmed robes
Thomas Nast illustrations (1860s-1880s) show a small, elf-like figure in various colors
The modern, standardized red suit is a 20th-century invention.
1.2 The Color of Generosity
Why green? The color symbolized:
Evergreen life (winter vitality, eternal hope)
Natural abundance (holly, ivy, mistletoe)
The forest spirit (pre-Christian winter celebrations)
Green was the color of non-commercial generosityâ€”the spontaneous, unmonetized gift of nature. It represented a giving that existed outside market logic, a generosity that could not be bottled, branded, or sold.
This was deeply problematic for emerging consumer capitalism.
II. The Coca-Cola Conspiracy: 1931 and the Birth of Red Santa
2.1 The Campaign
In 1931, Coca-Cola commissioned illustrator Haddon Sundblom to create a series of Santa Claus advertisements. The brief was explicit: create a warm, friendly, wholly human Santa who embodied the spirit of Coca-Cola.
Sundblom's Santa was:
Jolly and plump (suggesting abundant consumption)
Dressed in bright red (matching Coca-Cola's brand colors)
Holding a Coke (the not-so-subtle product placement)
Universally appealing (designed for mass-market reproduction)
The campaign ran for over 30 years and became the most widely distributed image of Santa Claus in history.
2.2 The Chromatic Coup
This was not merely advertisingâ€”it was cultural engineering. By saturating the market with a single, consistent image, Coca-Cola achieved something remarkable: they retroactively rewrote folklore.
Within two generations:
Green Santa was forgotten
Red became "traditional"
Coca-Cola's Santa became the Santa
Alternative depictions were viewed as inauthentic
The company had successfully executed a Chromatic Colonization: the corporate capture of a pre-commercial symbol system. They didn't just sell a product; they sold a reality.
2.3 The Monetization Formula
The genius of the campaign was its recursive self-justification:
Create a Santa who drinks Coca-Cola
Distribute the image globally for free (via advertising)
Wait for culture to adopt the image as "authentic"
Profit from the association between Christmas and consumption
The final step is crucial: once Santa became red, all Christmas became red. The color palette of the entire holiday season shifted to align with Coca-Cola's brand identity. Wrapping paper, decorations, greeting cardsâ€”all adopted the red-and-white scheme.
Coca-Cola didn't just advertise during Christmas; they architecturally restructured the holiday's visual language.
III. The Institutional Rebound: We Always Knew He Was Red
3.1 The Historical Amnesia
Ask anyone today: "What color is Santa's suit?"
The answer is instant, universal, and unquestioned: Red.
Ask why it's red: "Because... it's traditional?"
This is the ultimate institutional victory. The corporate origin has been so thoroughly erased that even mentioning it provokes cognitive dissonance. People respond as if you've suggested the sky is green.
"No, Santa has always been red. I remember it from when I was a child."
This is Implanted Nostalgiaâ€”the false memory of authenticity in something that was, from the beginning, a commercial construct.
3.2 The Rebranding of Generosity
The chromatic shift from green to red represents a deeper transformation: the commodification of giving.
Green Santa represented natural, seasonal generosityâ€”a gift economy
Red Santa represents consumer abundanceâ€”a market economy
The modern Christmas is no longer about the quiet generosity of winter; it's about optimized consumption logistics. Santa doesn't embody the spirit of giving; he embodies the spirit of getting everyone to buy stuff in Q4.
And yet, we defend this passionately as "tradition."
IV. The Final Twist: The Recursive Confession
4.1 The Inescapable Inside
At this point, having thoroughly dismantled the commercial mythology of Christmas, having exposed the red suit as corporate propaganda, having revealed Santa as a brand ambassadorâ€”we must now turn the blade inward.
Because here is the truth I cannot escape:
The "Holidays Are Coming" Coca-Cola advert is the best thing about Christmas.
Every year, without fail, the moment I see those illuminated trucks rolling through the snow, hear that haunting choir, and watch that impossibly perfect Santa waving from his Coca-Cola sleigh, I feel itâ€”the Christmas feeling.
Not because it's authentic. Not because it's traditional. But because it's perfectly executed emotional manipulation, and I love it.
4.2 The Guilty Pleasure Paradox
I am fully aware that:
The advert is a commercial for sugar water
The red suit is a corporate invention
The "magic" is manufactured nostalgia
The whole thing is designed to make me buy beverages
And yet, when those trucks appear on screen and the music swells, I am transported. I am eight years old again. Christmas is real. The world is good.
This is the ultimate institutional triumph: they have successfully implanted a Pavlovian response that overrides my critical faculties. I have been emotionally hacked, and I'm grateful for it.
4.3 The Capitulation
Therefore, in the spirit of rigorous self-critique, I must confess:
Coca-Cola was right to make Santa red.
Not because red is "traditional." Not because it's historically accurate. But because they created something genuinely beautiful in service of selling carbonated beverages, and that's oddly... magnificent?
The chromatic colonization was worth it. Green Santa is boring. Red Santa is iconic.
I have become the Black Knight defending the very system I set out to critique. My argument has been dismembered, yet here I stand, insisting "'Tis but a flesh wound! The holidays are coming, and I'm delighted about it!"
V. Seasonal Interlude: A Message to the Repository
5.1 The Physics Hiatus
To all who have followed this research program on GitHubâ€”thank you.
You've engaged with:
Galactic rotation curves
Cosmological curvature gradients
Curvature saturation models
Universal gravitational scaling
MTS field theory
Assorted satirical deconstructions of institutional logic
It's been a year of equations, datasets, and recursive paradoxes.
But now, as December unfolds and the illuminated trucks roll through the night, there will be no new physics papers for a few weeks.
Not because the research has stopped. Not because the patterns have ceased. But because even theoretical physicists need to eat too much food, argue with relatives, and watch adverts that shouldn't work but absolutely do.
5.2 The Holiday Privilege
Physics will wait. The universe has been expanding for 13.8 billion years; it can manage another fortnight without my GitHub commits.
Instead, I'll be doing what every human should do in late December:
Pretending to enjoy social gatherings
Eating experimentally large quantities of food
Watching the "Holidays Are Coming" advert on repeat
Feeling vaguely guilty about all of the above
Resolving to be more productive in January (a resolution that will last approximately 11 days)
This is the ritual. This is the tradition. And yes, it's all built on commercial foundations, but the foundations don't determine the meaning.
5.3 The Genuine Bit
So here's the real conclusion, the one that survives even recursive satire:
Thank you for reading this work.
Thank you for engaging with the absurdity, the rigor, the equations, the jokes, and the occasionally unhinged explorations of why institutions persist in defending their own obsolescence.
Thank you for tolerating papers that critique themselves, for following arguments that prove their own irrelevance, and for recognizing that sometimes the best way to understand a system is to laugh at it while standing inside it.
I hope your December is filled with:
Holidays Are Coming adverts (the pinnacle of human achievement)
Too much food (empirically necessary)
Questionable family dynamics (statistically unavoidable)
A brief, merciful pause from whatever institutional nonsense you're embedded in
And I hope, when January arrives and we all return to our respective delusions of productivity, you'll come back to the repository ready for another year of:
Empirical patterns
Computational models
Geometric hypotheses
And the occasional dismantling of things that should have stopped existing years ago
VI. Conclusion: Merry Chromatic Colonization to All
The Santa we know is a corporate invention. Christmas is a commercial construct. The "Holidays Are Coming" advert is emotional manipulation designed to sell sugar water.
And it's all absolutely wonderful.
Because here's the final truth: humans need rituals. We need shared stories, familiar music, and yes, even commercialized nostalgia. We need something that says, "The year is ending, the world is cold, but for a few weeks we can pretend everything is warm and lit and okay."
Does it matter that Coca-Cola built the iconography? Does it matter that the red suit is a branding exercise? Does it matter that the whole system is designed to extract value from our need for comfort?
No. Because the experience is real, even if the tradition is manufactured.
Santa may not be authentic, but the feeling he representsâ€”the hope that generosity exists, that someone is watching, that the good will be rewardedâ€”that feeling is as old as humanity itself.
Coca-Cola didn't create that. They just bottled it.
And honestly? They did a pretty good job.
